Josh Chapman

The Australian Institute of Sport data contains variables on height, weight, and other body measurements for elite male and female athletes training at the facility.

Objectives:

Executive Summary

My model seems like a very good predictor of body fat percentage. From the marginal model plot it is almost a perfect fit with the data. It does veer off at some points, but thats at points where there is not a lot of data so the variance is higher. The residual plots are evenly distributed around 0 with no clear pattern.

Tukey test Hypotheses: NH: = 0 versus AH: != 0. Corresponds to NH of no curvature of mean function versus AH that there is curvature. test statistic is 0.416 p-value = .677 Conclusion failure to reject the NH, there is not enough evidence to say that the mean function is curved.

Difference between Men and Women. Hypotheses: NH: No significant difference between fat percentage for men and women holding all predictors constant. AH: There is significant difference between fat percentage for men and women holding all predictors constant. test statistic 18.067 p-value <.0001 Conclusion we reject the NH and show that there is evidence for the AH. This means that there is some proof that holding all predictors constant there is a difference between fat percentage in Men and Women. The difference is estimated to be at exp(.867468) or 2.3808 more fat percentage for women than men.

NH: there is no difference in fat percentage between typically sized male and female basketball players AH: There is a difference in fat percentage between typically sized male and female basketball players upr bound for men is lower than the lwr bound for women so we can reject the NH and say that there is evidence that there is a difference between fat percentage for typically sized male and female basketball players given our data

The difference between typically sized male and female basketball players is that females have log(.653) or 1.92 more fat percentage than men.

General Summary of the route I took: I pretty much did everything in order from top down in this document except for the explanation. One thing I did have to go back for was the interpretation of the power transform. I didnt figure it out until I saw a red flag, which was that RCC behaved opposite for women than for men in my allEffects plot. It really didnt make sense to me so I reevaluated my model. Then found out that I need to so some more transformations. Doing that fixed the weirdness of RCC and Sex. It was a pain to restructure everything though.

In general from the effects plots it looks like as height is a negative predictor for fat, RCC is a positive predictor, and weight is a positve predictor.

Using the Anova command to see if there are any interactions in the model. There were three interactions that had a p-value less than .05 Sex and RCC, Sex and Ht, RCC and Wt interact. I created a new model based on this evidence.

testmodel <- lm(Bfat ~ (Sex + RCC + Wt + Ht)^2 , data=ais)

Creating a regression tree to see the most influential predictor variables. From this initial tree it looks like Sex is the most influential predictor followed by Wt then Ht. I then made another tree that was trimmed using the values I got from printcp I thought that .03 looked like a good point to trim. The new tree cut out Ht which suggests that it might not be as important.

treeobject1<-rpart(Bfat ~ Sex + RCC + Wt + Ht, data=ais)

Checking to see if transforms on predictors are needed. The power transform output tells me we should log everything except for Ht.

I then did a check to see if a transformation is needed for the response variable using inverseResponsePlot and boxCox. From the boxcox and inverse response plot it looks like doing a log transform on the response would be a good choice so I created a new model based on this. I also did an inverse response plot on the new model but it didnt suggest that any transformations were needed so I didnt include it.

Comparing men who play basketball to women. Had to create a new model blogmodel that includes sports so I could compare basketball players. Interpretation is included above. I realize that I should have used a linear combination, but I couldnt get it to quite work. It runs but it didnt seem to make sense given the previous data. I do believe that the code that I have below still has enough proof to support the claims I made in my interpretation. Answer to question 3

blogmodel <- lm(log(Bfat) ~ Sex + log(RCC) + log(Wt) + Ht + Sex:log(RCC) + Sex:log(Wt) + log(RCC):log(Wt), data=ais)

predict(blogmodel, data.frame(Sex="Male", RCC=4.7, Ht=201, Wt = 90, Sport = "b_ball"), interval = "confidence", level=.95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 2.166458 2.075576 2.257339
predict(blogmodel, data.frame(Sex="Female", RCC=4.7, Ht=180, Wt = 70, Sport = "b_ball"), interval = "confidence", level=.95)
##        fit     lwr      upr
## 1 2.819002 2.75313 2.884874

bais <- ais[which(ais$Sport==b_ball), ]

blogmodel2 <- lm(log(Bfat) ~ Sex + log(RCC) + log(Wt) + Ht + Sex:log(RCC) + Sex:log(Wt) + log(RCC):log(Wt), data=bais)

avect <- c(0, 0, 4.7, 90, 201, 4.7, 180, 70, 0) elhat <- sum(avect * coef(blogmodel2)) stdelhat <- sqrt(t(avect) %% vcov(blogmodel2) %% avect) cbounds <- c(elhat - 1.96 * stdelhat, elhat + 1.96 * stdelhat) c(elhat, stdelhat, cbounds)
